351 And that through unfailing signs we might learn these dangers—the heat, and the rain, and the cold- bringing winds—the Father himself decreed what warning the monthly moon should give, what should signal the fall of the wind, and what sight, oft seen, should prompt the sarmer to keep his cattle nearer to their stalls. From the first, when the winds are rising, either the sea's straits begin to heave and swell, and on mountain-heights is heard a dry erash, or the shores ring a confused echo afar and the wood- land murmur waxes loud.
